   "source": [
    "## Executive Summary:\n",
    "\n",
    "This report is about predicting housing sale prices. To predict the prices two data sets were used, one is the Housing_Data_Train.csv and another one is Housing_Data_Test.csv.\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine you have a dataset of houses with various features like size, number of bedrooms, when built, when sold, etc., and you want to predict their prices. The goal is to build a model that makes accurate predictions without being too simple or too complex.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here's what the code does:\n",
    "\n",
    "It starts by loading the housing data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Then, it splits the data into two parts: the \"training\" set and the \"validation\" set. The training set is used to teach the model how to make predictions, and the validation set is used to check how well the model is doing.\n",
    "\n",
    "The code creates a linear regression model, which is a way to make predictions based on the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "It trains the model using the training data, so the model learns from the features of the houses and their actual prices.\n",
    "\n",
    "After training, the model makes predictions on the validation set and calculates how accurate those predictions are.\n",
    "\n",
    "It repeats these steps while varying the complexity of the model. In simpler terms, it tries to build models that are too simple, models that are just right, and models that are too complex.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, it plots a graph that shows how well each model performs. This graph has a U-shape, and here's what it means:\n",
    "\n",
    "On the left side of the U (the simple models), both the training and validation errors are high. This is underfitting because the model is too basic to make good predictions.\n",
    "In the middle of the U, the errors are the lowest. This is the \"sweet spot\" where the model is just right in terms of complexity.\n",
    "\n",
    "On the right side of the U (the complex models), the training error becomes very low, but the validation error starts going up. This is overfitting because the model is too complex and starts making bad predictions on new data.\n",
    "In essence, the code shows that finding the right balance in model complexity is crucial. Too simple or too complex models both lead to poor predictions. The goal is to strike the right balance in the middle of the U-shaped curve where the model generalizes well to new, unseen data."
   ]
  },
  {

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9aa60423",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data Pre-Processing:\n",
    "At first, a train data set for predicting housing sale price was loaded using Pandas DataFrame in a two-dimensional tabular data structure. \n",
    "In the first step of data pre-processing, the first column name was changed from \"Unnamed: 0\" to \"Serial No\" using a Pandas method named rename(). In a similar process, the test data set was loaded using Pandas DataFrame and the first column was renamed as  \"Serial No\" using the rename() method.\n",
    "Then the missing and Not-a-Number (NaN) values of the train data set were replaced with 0 using a Pandas method named fillna(). In the third step, the data set was extracted into features (X) and target (y) set."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "5d90495d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Load train and test data set:\n",
    "train_data = pd.read_csv(\"Housing_Data_Train.csv\")\n",
    "train_data = train_data.rename(columns = {\"Unnamed: 0\":\"Serial No\"})\n",
    "test_data = pd.read_csv(\"Housing_Data_Test.csv\")\n",
    "test_data = test_data.rename(columns = {\"Unnamed: 0\":\"Serial No\"})\n",
    "train_data = train_data.fillna(0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "272fcd27",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Separate features (X) and target (y)\n",
    "X = train_data[[\"Id\", \"MSSubClass\", \"LotFrontage\", \"LotArea\", \"OverallQual\", \"OverallCond\", \"YearBuilt\", \"YrSold\"]]\n",
    "y = train_data[\"SalePrice\"]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4fe9deb4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Modelling and Model Tuning:\n",
    "\n",
    "At this point, the training data was split into training and validation sets using the train_test_split() method from model_selection in scikit learn. Here, 'X_train' and 'y_train' are the feature matrix and target variable for the training set, that are used as the machine learning model to train the data. Furthermore, to evaluate the performance of your trained model 'X_val' and 'y_val' are the the feature matrix and target variable for the validation set. \n",
    "\n",
    "To ensure the data was split in the same way while running the code multiple times and get a consistent result the 'random_state' parameter value was fixed to 42.\n",
    "\n",
    "'test_size' argument mainly specifies the percentage of data allocated for validation set. In this case, different values were used to fit the model between 20% - 50% (0.2 - 0.5).\n",
    "\n",
    "The model was fitted with Linear Regression to predict values for feature matrix-based target variable, which was stored in 'y_val_pred'. This was done using the LinearRegression() method from linear_model in the scikit learn library.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) were measured by the mean_squared_error() method from metrics in the scikit learn. The best result found for 'test_size' value 0.4, which means 40% of data was used for validation and 60% for training the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "7b90f7cd",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Split the training data into training and validation sets\n",
    "X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.4, random_state=42)\n",
    "# Fitting the model using Linear Regression\n",
    "lr_model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "lr_model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "y_val_pred = lr_model.predict(X_val)"
   ]
  },

    "mse = mean_squared_error(y_val, y_val_pred)\n",

    "# Calculate the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) on the validation set\n",
    "rmse = mean_squared_error(y_val, y_val_pred, squared=False)\n",

    "# Create lists to store training and validation errors\n",
    "train_errors = []\n",
    "val_errors = []\n",
    "\n",
    "# Vary the degree of polynomial features\n",
    "degrees = range(1, 10)  # You can adjust this range as needed\n",
    "\n",
    "for degree in degrees:\n",
    "    # Create polynomial features\n",
    "    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)\n",
    "    X_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(X)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Split the data into training and validation sets\n",
    "    X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X_poly, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Initialize and train a Linear Regression model\n",
    "    lr_model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "    lr_model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculate training and validation errors (Root Mean Squared Error)\n",
    "    train_pred = lr_model.predict(X_train)\n",
    "    val_pred = lr_model.predict(X_val)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    train_error = mean_squared_error(y_train, train_pred, squared=False)\n",
    "    val_error = mean_squared_error(y_val, val_pred, squared=False)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    train_errors.append(train_error)\n",
    "    val_errors.append(val_error)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the training and validation errors\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.plot(degrees, train_errors, label=\"Training Error\", marker='o')\n",
    "plt.plot(degrees, val_errors, label=\"Validation Error\", marker='o')\n",
    "plt.title(\"Overfitting vs. Underfitting (Polynomial Regression)\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Degree of Polynomial Features\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Root Mean Squared Error\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

    "#### Overfitting (High Complexity):\n",
    "\n",
    "As we use a large number of features (close to the total number), the model becomes too complex. Training error decreases significantly because the model can fit the training data very well, including noise. Validation error starts increasing because the model fails to generalize to unseen data, resulting in poor performance. The \"U\"-shaped curve has the validation error increasing while the training error decreases.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Balanced Fit (Optimal Complexity):\n",
    "\n",
    "There's an optimal number of features that results in the lowest validation error. The model is not too simple or too complex, achieving a good balance. Both training and validation errors are relatively low and close to each other in this region",
    "\n",
    "#### Underfitting (Low Complexity):\n",
    "\n",
    "As we use too few features, the model is overly simplistic. Training error increases because the model cannot capture the underlying patterns in the data. Validation error remains high because the model lacks the complexity to generalize.\n",
    "The \"U\"-shaped curve shows both training and validation errors increasing as complexity decreases. The generalization gap, represented by the difference between training and validation errors, is an important indicator. In the overfitting scenario, this gap is large, indicating poor generalization. In the underfitting scenario, the gap is smaller but the errors are high, indicating both training and validation errors are bad.\n",
    "\n",
    "The balanced fit scenario demonstrates the point at which the model achieves the best trade-off between bias (underfitting) and variance (overfitting), resulting in the lowest validation error."
   ]
